Color in alcohol. Plain black, gray or dark brown, sometimes with darker spots. Degree of spotting or vermiculations varies among populations, and among individuals of same population. Specimens from Panama and Atrato River (
Fig. 6
) have very few dark spots and those from Baudó River in Pacific Colombia most heavily spotted (
Fig. 5
). Spots on fins more conspicuous than those on body in many specimens. Spots on the dorsal fin often consist of oblique dashes on membranes. See ‘Remarks’.

Distribution. Pacific drainages of southeast Panama (Bayano and Tuira river drainages) and Colombia (Chocó Region San Juan, Dagua, and Baudó rivers), and the Atrato River basin, which empties into the Caribbean Sea in northwest Colombia (
Fig. 4
).
